Hi Constantin,

>One of your answers seems not to be correct:
>
>http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/54544.html
>"In cases where f(g(x)) = g(f(x)), the functions are inverses of each 
>other. " 
>The converse is true, but they don't have to be the inverse of each
other.
>
>e.g. :  f(x)=1/x,  g(x)=-x      f(g(x))=-1/x = g(f(x))

You're right.  We've corrected that.  Thanks for catching it!

